Ukraine's parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal a paragraph under the amendment to the Criminal Code, on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted.
The amendment, which would open the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-premier, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of a proposal to ease the penalties for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for entering into a supposedly unfavourable contract with Russia to buy natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the appeal of the convicted person is due to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko calls the ruling a political revenge of the regime, the suspicion of the bias of the court sparked a trial even in the West.
The proposal to remove Article 365 from the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the ex-premier was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
It was required to approve 226 votes.
