The diet of an obese child: does not eat and dinner sausages
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, with 9 percent of schoolchildren weighing overweight and 5 percent of children.
Obese children usually come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as the current survey has shown.
It shows once again how important the environment in which he grows up is important for the healthy development of a person and the patterns he is surrounded by.
On the tables of obese children, for example, sausages appear up to half more often than in families of children with normal weight.
The fried fries had for dinner the day before the research associated with the awareness event called Obesity is no coincidence more than 19 percent of the obese.
It is also not customary to play sports in the families of fat people, but this applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children replied that their parents will find time to move actively at least once a week.
Survey among 900 children
The survey took place at the end of last school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of the Obesity event is not a coincidence, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand schoolchildren from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Proper eating and plenty of exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatically increasing number of children who are overweight or even obese.
"Only half of respondents, for example, said that they eat five times a day in the breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," reads one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and no sausage in the evening
Experts warn that relative details, such as regular family breakfast time, are also essential for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst was finding that in a tenth of households, breakfast doesn't even have breakfast.
Breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are much more often consumed.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of children surveyed regularly play sports, their parents had a less than half-percent result.
Build your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to assemble their own diet according to their own taste and own opinion from the offered options.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from the ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"What is particularly alarming is the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on the survey said.
For lunch as the main meal, pasta won just above the poultry.
However, the children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetable dishes is also low.
Proceedings to Health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"There is no coincidence for the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the awareness lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, in many cases there has been a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy eating," the project results state.
This was striking, for example, in sweet lemonades, where more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children also ticked poultry and fish as the main meal of the day in the questionnaire much more often and would limit sweet food and dumplings.
