In Need for Speed: The Run, racing across America.
Reviews
The originally carefree ride, due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes, turns into a routine morning trip to the shift.
The ambition was largely fulfilled, but it is of no use if no one apparently wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, was high expectations before the release.
He promised that the age-old racing series Need for Speed would again move a bit in a new direction and from playable demonstrations appeared to be a game that might not be just in number in the genre of action racing.
We were also curious about how the inserted passages will turn out, in which the main character gets out of the car and will take place on his own.
However, as is customary with the NFS series, many are a little different than we expected.
They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole drags down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing more or less in the series for several years.
So it's not even mistakes, but rather a manifestation of the incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal character and as a solution offers participation in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea brings with it some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is run on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t feel like the game is always the same.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-class.
But driving across deserts, autumn landscapes or high in snowy mountains looks visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are from time to time diversified by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught up in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
In contrast, in the mountains, you need to be careful not to be covered by an avalanche.
In addition, individual races are quite well planted behind.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up with time (classic fight with stopwatch) and then you have a duel with a single opponent.
The police will get involved from time to time, which makes your efforts even more difficult.
New are the passages outside the car.
Rather, it is just interactive animations, when Jack usually flees from someone and you have to help him by printing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
It surprises, however, that these passages are in play much less than you would expect (specifically, perhaps even three).
As a result, however, it is for the benefit of the matter, because this element has no chance to become annoying and in the context of the above is thus one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
This means that it is definitely not who knows what, but it cannot be said that it is a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will need to look elsewhere.
But the more action-oriented racing of the local driving model still suits quite well, although we could find better in the competition.
Until now, everything is in perfect order.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the model is not very well.
We do not expect the game of this type to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea before any impact on any object, how your car will behave, then probably everything is not quite right.
Typically, when you overtake or pass cars in normal traffic, sometimes you just lick each other easily, but other times in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even attack.
Thanks to the restart system, it does not matter much, but it will make you very disilly.
The restarts are designed in such a way that if you smash or go far off the track, the game will throw you back on the last point on the track.
There are only five restarts in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it's more of a tool in case something goes wrong than that you can explicitly rely on them.
Sometimes even restarts do not help, they will be solved by the need to learn the given section of the race by heart.
The big ailment of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can not fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It annoys especially in situations when you see the opponent passing easily between two oncoming cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "counted" so that the situation always occurs just before your nose.
Opponents also have another advantage.
In the whole time of playing, you will come across several places where you, again, regardless of time, will always overtake the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously get there in front of you at any cost.
When driving in front of you, it makes your overview of oncoming cars worse, so you can use a few times there.
It is possible to understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-inducing, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably quickly disgust you.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes even so actionable that sometimes you literally can't watch where it flies.
And it doesn’t really matter whether it’s due to the concept with fifty unique tracks, the gearshift of races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance or anything else.
The unconventional idea is to replace cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas stations by the road, because that is where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you can do with what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars for straight highways and exotic supercars for technical riding, for example, on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the mode of challenges, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common for challenges and story.
For obtaining a higher level of the driver, various items are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
It is also connected to the online Autolog feature, which, among other things, compares your achievements with other players and provides additional community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can get to the subway tunnel (so be it) where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (so be it).
On the speedometer, the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (so be it) flash and in this the subway train comes in from behind and uncompromisingly scraps you.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a few more days to discuss whether no one really thought a little bit when creating the game, or whether the authors think we are really such a big jerk.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It freezes so that in some more tense moments the imaging decreases, in some cases quite tragically.
However, this applies especially to crashes with a larger number of participants, when smooth imaging would be of no use to you anyway.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack was created from the category "each dog different village", but it can be assumed that due to listening to music, the game will probably not be bought by anyone.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so embarrassing.
If the game avoids completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of NFS in the last few years.
This is how the game is unfinished.
The fun is definitely fine, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will smash you into the eyes with the power of airport spotlights.
The UK choirs will be performed at the concert Students of Velvet
The Festa Academica festival is offering a combination of the celebrations of the International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with the musical experience for the third time.
During it, he will present himself at twenty high school and college choirs.
The main focus of the festival is two concerts held on 17 November.
"Charles University has a large stake in the festival."
"Among the participating choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, the festival committee will include the Rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, the head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the whole festival is a free concert of high school choirs, which will take place on 17 November at 2 p.m. in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme includes a composition by the prominent Czech jazzman Karel Růžička Celebration Jazz Mass.
