Ambassador to the EU Vicen:
Czechs have a reputation for having negatives and Eurosceptics
"The Treaty of Lisbon has significantly disrupted the balance between the institutions."
"I didn't expect it to be such a tough war."
"It will take five, six years for the situation to stabilize a little, calm down and for all players to get used to their new roles," Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicenová began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
To the extent that she takes her motto "Comprehensively and openly about Europe" seriously, she already showed in the first part of the lecture, when she managed to describe the individual EU institutions and their relations in such a clear and understandable way that a number of lecturers from the Faculty of Law of the Charles University could envy her.
Vicen also praised the work of the new Permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first there was criticism that he was lackluster, that he was a grey official, that he couldn't play any role, and I had to say that everyone was taking a breather, that he did the role well."
"He is a man who can listen to twenty-seven Member States, communicate with them well and has a clear vision of where the European Union should go."
She then explained the new post of High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy in response to the question: "Who is this European Union? Which phone number should I call?", as an important step towards the unification and greater readability of EU policy towards states such as China or India.
No one wants to ban us from cheese
Vicenová also devoted herself to the agenda that the European Council lived, lives and will live in the near future.
The Czech Presidency described it as a success.
The Czechs dealt with the oncoming financial crisis, resolved the gas crisis or held a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
The fall of the government at this time was described as a big negative, which damaged the Czech Republic very badly.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
In the words of the ambassador, the "fact of the problem" was not only the presidency, but also the subsequent financial crisis, which is still being solved today.
Moreover, the new seven-year Union budget has yet to be approved, which is very complicated because of the current economic situation.
Whether the budget will be lean and austere, which sectors will be given priority, which countries will be supported more and which less, all of which is on the agenda for the next negotiations.
The ambassador also recalled her main slogans, with which she came to Brussels: "On Europe intelligible."
"I really don't like ugly shortcuts, foreign words, a mischief that no one understands.
How is a citizen supposed to understand that in Brussels there are no curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes or that someone really has to ban us from cheese.”
It also wants to make better use of the EU environment and get more Czechs into European institutions.
We have a multi-speed Europe
According to the ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics and people who notice the negative than positive aspects of things.
Moreover, she regrets the low representation of Czechs in European institutions.
According to her, a lot of factors are to blame, for example, the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational letters, but also low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
"Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak approach, the Frenchman next to me will say, "Hey, what are you meeting there, what about your Visegrad Four?" and he doesn't look excited about it at all."
In the future, according to Vicenová, the Union will face mainly new tough rules on the budgetary policies of the member countries.
He perceives the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe, rather than a new "European Federation."
"We have eurozone countries and countries outside the eurozone."
"We have a Schengen area, we already have an institute of enhanced cooperation."
"For the first time, it was said that only the countries they wanted and those who did not want to cooperate should be near."
"There will be more institutes and it will be a strongly two-speed Europe," Vicen said.
In this respect, it also appreciated the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the principle that all topics that have an impact on the whole Union are to be discussed among all Member States, not only among euro area countries.
Brand story:
The IBM innovator begins the second century of its existence
If someone were looking for a word that most accurately expresses IBM's strategy, the closest thing would probably be "long-term."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The basis of this long-term was laid by the first boss of the company, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that a number of the world's problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became an imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine that began to be published at IBM in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully constructed corporate culture.
“For us from IBM, long-term thinking means a continuous move towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values and was not afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
