How have the prices of tours evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia at that time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies were overwhelmingly only selling tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within socialist countries.
In the event that a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual route was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand the queue overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to get funds (western currency) for the trip to the West.
However, by far most often the Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 the holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible to travel freely to our most popular Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austrian Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to visit there for a little while.
For example, in Paris, Czechs slept in parks in tents, because our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of the travel of Czechs at this time was to drive their own food, canned food, sausages, etc. to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which allows our tourists to finally buy the western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with that average salaries rose, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have regularly started preparing tours with charter air services since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper thanks to the possibility to negotiate quantity discounts compared to the past.
By the late 1990s, Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first ever direct charter flight to exotica was dispatched from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
From this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm distant countries, this winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100 thousand Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the USA revoked visas for Czech tourists and thus our country was definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%) and spent more than 15 thousand for one foreign holiday for the first time in their history, including the cost of their whereabouts. CZK per person.
