Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book, Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with such a long list of performing characters that you get dizzy.
One piece of advice on how to behave at that moment: Carefully rip this page out and make a bookmark of it.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund's novel story, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a kind of beacon - when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "antihistorical work."
It contains several very well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, but rather "a book about what it was like." It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" combines the wartime experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from female students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of fates, while others quench.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It regulates the notion that the First World War was just about the fearsome trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and grief" explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
