Facebook is constantly probing its users’ data.
The information team of the website has prepared statistics on the context of relational statuses and St. Valentine's Day, turnout in 2010 and the coefficient of satisfaction of the nation (mainly using the information to which they had access - proponents of Internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available to others).
But Facebook users know that the page tracks them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the ability to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the page needs to be provided with your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
