Climate adversity has hampered the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's rule, unemployment and unreliability rose in Sinaloa, and foreign investment declined, and with it the economy
2011 will be in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the reign of Mario López Valdez, which calls itself the government of change. This government has brought with it high expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth and even a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
Low February temperatures have caused million-dollar losses in agriculture, limiting the growth of the state economy, and reducing economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. There was a historic decline of 31.16% in agriculture, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded on 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were found to be partial damage. The main crops destroyed include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a steady rise in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state saw an increased increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55 053 residents of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing a unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment rose to 5.28%, and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise, reaching 6.19%, representing around 74,000 unemployed. Compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed people increased by 18 969 people.
Less liquidity
There are more factors for unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa. According to Gerard López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps taken at the level of public policy.
"We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors. These include, among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market due to the limitations of resources due to legislation passed by Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. It's not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn them, invest them or use them for something," he stressed.
Stop migration
López Cervantes said the demographic factor also contributed to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work, to the United States, has decreased, both because of difficult entry and because even if these people go abroad, it's hard for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is rising,” he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the global labour market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability that prevails in the field of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of employed residents in the state work without paying benefits to the Social Security Administration.
Other features of the labour market, such as low salaries, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries are from across the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5 352 pesets by September, well below the national average, which is at 7 375 pesetas.
Shortening of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was also recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, between January and June, foreign direct investment amounted to 630 697 dollars, representing a decrease of 87.74% compared to 5 143 312 dollars for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the Government of the State lists investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year. These investments were mainly directed to service companies.
Debt
In the context of the scenario of a downturn in the economy, the government of that state asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso. It would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million peso. There were no profits from debt until November, in no sector of the state economy.
Reaction
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés pointed out the lack of governing capabilities of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformational Industries, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the government of the state itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been really slight during this year. We need to work hard to get back the ground we've lost this year. In 2012 we must redouble our efforts, the harmonisation of the efforts of all of us, and especially the proper and synchronized functioning of this new government, was lacking. Hopefully next year will be much better,” he said.
The slowness of the economy
Loredo López said events like frosts at the beginning of the year halted the state economy and curtailed its development and growth.
"Weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore the dynamism that would enable the movement of processes, products and services to be reached. That’s why we were well below the expected forecasts at the end of the year,” he said.
Redefining the mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employer Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamically productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we observe that we are working. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has is mobilized.”
The work that is ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better manage the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in different areas, there have been some advances in economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
He stated that the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be welcoming. I can say that there is a job done here and I think that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us.”
