The quintet included the country in its tour to mark the twenty years of existence
"The road to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the group is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that the opportunity for them to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is located on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate twenty years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20.
This day will perform from 19:30 at the National Stadium along with the angelic group The X and national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from an interview, the entire transcript of which can be found on the La Nación website on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The road to Costa Rica is also our dream, which becomes a reality.
In South and Central America we are barely the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a beautiful country and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we're so happy to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally adore the group here, fans experience these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you think to your most rocky supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for such a long number of years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already refer to the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we've shown in the last 21 years have come out in a few weeks.
We have put on some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that this puts us in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing Costa Rica or Nicaragua, or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And so we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we don't have any limitations on what we can't do.
We will try to show the best possible show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think it's partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose what songs we're going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it already.
That's how the show is more interesting to us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
With this tour you celebrate 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I think that none of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years. That sounds like a dream.
We realize how much it has given us and we are moved that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are fortunate to be able to look at the places we have always longed for.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the greats themselves are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at once.
We are proud of this and we are honoured to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we went to the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are fortunate that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, we four have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the group's usual duration.
I think, first of all, we are all lucky that we are still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone with sufficient freedom to experiment with themselves.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word glory was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
The way we grew, it was gradually getting easier to find balance.
We try not to go too much on tour because it's very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remember that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You can't get carried away by being famous, rock stars. Neither of us really cared about that.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and it was something spectacular in the beginning.
We existed as a band for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the pictures, I remember Andy being incredible, how I laughed with him. It has always been a joy to work with him, to laugh, to talk about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss him so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be tasked with launching a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the front-rooters?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. That's why we're curious about what Las Robertas will offer live and have to be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yellow Ledbetter?
That's the question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
I'm the first to think of Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I could talk all night about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge, even though it's no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt lightly separated from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I imagine groups I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out at the same time. And if music is still valid like this today, it's something great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and groups like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly bleak character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there's a couple of tracks in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very bleak, although they may sound positive.
For both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
