Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss, which he suffers in the lower limbs area, his attending physician reported.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is already under the control of doctors.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told the television station Canal N that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days, where they should find out why he hurts and why he loses strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his view Fujimori could receive a pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, the former president himself does not wish to pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times because of tongue cancer, he lost 18 kilograms, and other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs were added to these problems, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving a sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his rule.
Mujica on a visit to Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, led by Uruguayan President, José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday. It aims to achieve trade expansion between the two nations and to touch on the political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet with her Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of a large-scale visit to full meetings with representatives of the policy, trade and representatives of the Urugua community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan presidential office.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will serve to exchange information about political matters between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office posted on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy placed the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that would continue to remain in the position of tax havens would be excluded from the international community. The statement drew a negative position from Uruguay and consultation with the ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has presided over the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries. The Latin American country has an agreement on the exchange of information to prevent double taxation from January this year.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to concretize fiscal exchange agreements to get off the "blacklist" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), to which there are countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of tax cooperation.
From a trade point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have been signed the Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has resulted in a strengthening of the exchange of goods between the two countries.
