The city's tender for 16 gates again opens the debate over the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the time of the greatest flourishing of the already extinct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What's more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
After the CMB disappeared in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper frontier of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that does not focus on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park is going in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of the Yogi bear.
Such was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, plays the idea of a park.
Either this or someone is trying to place the gate in the field.
So there's only one question: Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both in terms of purely organizational and reflection on the city, this question becomes the central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It is already a topic as wiped as when two members of this old caste of the chosen ones shake hands during a meeting in the elevator.
And it was this feat that triggered one of the rare matches between what three Barcelona architects and pre-receiving university professors think.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayon: the selection process is justified.
