Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash in which the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others were killed.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of an accident investigation in which the secretary of the government, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others were killed, show that the helicopter hit the terrain directly with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the aircraft took off, the pilot said the climatic conditions allowed the flights.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings became entangled in the branches of the trees 25 meters from where the unit lost its hull."
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, therefore it met all the requirements for the transfer of personnel.
In addition, he said that based on an investigation carried out in the impact area, no parts were found on the ground.
"In the search, it was found that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft hit the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, meeting all the requirements for transporting people.
The terrain exhibits a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, general manager of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft upward terrain.
“This information supports the hypothesis that it was a normal overflight operation at the time of the accident,” he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome listed six base points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at takeoff, according to which the aircraft is moving towards the border, between DF and State Mexico were noticeable layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and more visibility all the way to the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The crash coordinates and the last recording of the helicopter from the radar agree, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the trajectory of the flight before the impact.
Dispersion of aircraft residues in restricted areas:
The information we currently have at our disposal allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A sketch of the dispersal of the plane's remains suggests that at the time of the impact on the mainland, the helicopter was whole.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the crash that indicated that there had been an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the fieldwork, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain slopes, the amount of slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show footage that probably broke up along the route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After careful search in the vicinity of the accident, in a territory that is more extensive than the territory of the demarcation, the remains of the helicopter were not found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still whole.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has launched research into a gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "The Genetics of Obesity in Children and Young People" will allow you to obtain results related to being overweight.
In a report, the head of the Research Medical Unit in the field of biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Health Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and students of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, who have or have no authority, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where tests for juveniles will be performed every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He emphasized that the research began at the Cuahtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and from 8. October this activity is also carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are retrieved, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of obesity development, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people to prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are made anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, trigliceride, cholesterol, insulin is determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify the genes involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said this research reflects health workers' concern over the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health polls conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys experienced an increase in obesity of 77% and in girls by 47%. There has also been a dramatic increase in the case of overweight', said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetics, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes responsible for the emergence of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy, which we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive a general assessment of the condition of the children, thus determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acantosis) in the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-candy conditions.
The information is confidential so far, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to prevent their children from having the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life meaning a lack of daily physical activity, all-day sitting in front of the TV, and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
Excess weight is also caused by a large calorie intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in the Asphalt of UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving were properly taken care of, there would be no need to repair almost 200 thousand potholes after each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, pointed out Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) from UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt cobbles were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even could be completely removed.
In his lecture, the technological cause of the potholes, which he uttered during the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, thus creating a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and at high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example, in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt, the heaviest part of the oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular mass, which are called asphaltens, and others with low molecular weight, which are called maltenes. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of the asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, the expert on chemical engineering pointed out.
A scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible paving, consisting of six layers of materials, the last of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the uppermost layers is an asphalt insert, made up of small stones poured in the asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms a liner is wrapped with asphalt.
When cars are passed or when creating pressure, it is possible that the forces in the pavement are well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, it would be even better, a chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer called the mantle, made up of fine stones, also covered with sand in the asphalt, is placed on the asphalt insert.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rims, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since it will be subjected to a heavy load as part of the paving, the sheath must have sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is damp, the water spreads inwards and it is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the pavement and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the creation of potholes, the film of the cloak is the first to be damaged, and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one time, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first grades using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in the creation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tiles must correspond to the load on vehicles and must be guaranteed that this load will not be exceeded. This is the only way to prevent the frequent formation of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to the asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and the research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
