Such was the work of the resident of Cali, who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A fingerprint expert from Cali has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4 last year, a CTI fingerprint expert in Cali entered history as a man who confirmed the identity of Supreme Leader Farc: "Alfonse Cano," through a comparison of fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working in the CTI department this week, it was the turn of Eliazar González, a man from Puerta Tejad, who has been working in the field of judicial research for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked at the town hall in Chocó, where he often had to make his way through the forest for more than five days to get to the place where the corpses had to be identified.
He moved to the capital, Valle, in 2000, and after taking the appropriate courses, began specializing in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of the friction of the skin, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week that the operation was performed against the said Alfonsi Cana, the Eliazars were told to bring clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night, he set off for Cauco in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he would have to identify two corpses and that he suspected that one of them was the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world. That's why they asked him to take a card with the fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigating team at the place where the corpse was located, he did not recognize it because of his physical appearance. He looked very different than in the media.
He didn't have a beard, dressed as a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with the galton magnifying glass, the ink and the transplanter and the light, Eliazar began to compare the dactyl records of the corpse with the card entries.
The eye did not disappoint him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
The same night, a man originally from Puerto Tejada was commissioned to confirm to Defense Secretary Juan Carlos Pinzón whether he was really the commander-in-chief of Farc.
Searching for clues
For the dactyl scope from Sijín de Cali, the recognition shown to Eliazar González by President Juan Manuel Santos at a press conference of the operational service against "Can" is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, which can play a key role in decision-making of crimes.
In addition to identifying the corpses, these people assist in the research of crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identity of the persons caught.
When they get caught, a lot of delinquents present fake IDs or don't have papers at all.
We're gonna take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator recounted that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the wall of the house in the house, because at this place the thief was relying to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not intended for fingerprinting, but in this case we could get a full-hand print and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also confirm or refute suspicions in a murder case.
Not long ago, they found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
Based on the investigation, it was found that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder and the imprint on the bottle actually confirmed it.
Although it cannot be confirmed that he was indeed a murderer, it is clear that he appeared on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint expert explained that fingerprints are "blurred from objects using chemical or physical reactive substances."
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used for their collection.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, which is a database of delinquents, or to the Registrature.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians whose data are not entered anywhere," the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as shown on the CSI television program.
Like everything that glitters, there is no gold, not everything you touch, traces remain.
However, if it can be used, the relevant comparison must be made.
