Nord Stream, the new entry port of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream remote pipeline connecting directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea has begun to operate.
It must supply gas equal to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including 4 heads of state and government, took part in the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together the control round the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will start flowing every year to Western Europe with the first pipeline with a length of 1 224 km connecting the region of St. Petersburg with the federal state of Mecklemburg-Pomorany.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of r. 2012 will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is the amount that is equal to the entire French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline of the pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly objected to the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow the supply of gas directly to Germany without being routed by a third state (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, the two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats to close access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it strongest when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", citing the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in r. 1939.
It means saying it's a politically sensitive subject.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained more certainty of its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created cracks between Europeans from the East and West.
Russia has barely managed to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of this pipeline, demonstrating at what point the big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of the Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of concrete sheath steel to protect it from the anchors of naval vessels.
It rests on the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the period of World War 2.
“Because of the security, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations anywhere in its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see the Russian state company permanently settling off their coast.
"In case of a fault, we stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute," Jens Müller specifies.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered by the builder to be unlikely, after all, the welds were designed to create the leak once every 100 000 years.
The inspection of the condition of the pipeline from the outside is carried out by an undersea robot drawn by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the interior of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the destination over a full three days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about any deformations of metal parts.
The long-range pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the need for the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream in charge of the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transport capacities for five years with a contract that can be renewed.
"Gazprom will make a profit on the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was ensured by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, investment costs have risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be repaid, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The 4.5-meter high valves form the output gate of the gas.
The sensor measures the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before being transported to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When the full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in r. 2012 6 million.
